  Title      : Stanford AI Seminar

  Starts In  : 0d 18h 15m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. context_update: ```markdown# Screenshot 1**Application:** Safari**Search Query:** what are the defalt hyperparameters in openai api**Content:**- **AI Overview**    The OpenAI API utilizes various hyperparameters with default values that influence the behavior of models during text generation and fine-tuning. These defaults are in place unless explicitly overridden by the user in their API requests.    **Key Default Hyperparameters in OpenAI API:**    - **Temperature:** Controls the randomness of the output. The default value is often 1.0 or 0.7, depending on the specific model used. A higher temperature leads to more diverse and creative outputs, while a lower temperature results in more deterministic and focused outputs.    - **Top_p:** Determines the portion of the highest probability tokens to select from during text generation. The default value is typically 1.0, meaning the model considers all tokens within the top probability mass. Lowering top_p narrows the selection to only the most probable tokens, making the output less random.    - **Presence Penalty:** Influences the probability of output tokens based on their presence in the generated output. This can help to reduce repetition. The default value is usually 0.0.    - **Frequency Penalty:** Affects the probability of output tokens based on their frequency of occurrence in the generated output. This also helps to reduce repetition by penalizing frequently occurring tokens. The default value is typically 0.0.    - **Best_of:** Specifies the number of completions to generate and return the "best" one based on log probability. The default is 1, meaning only one completion is generated.    - **Stream:** A boolean parameter indicating whether to stream the response back in chunks. The default is False.    - **Stop:** A sequence of tokens that, if encountered, will cause the model to stop generating further tokens. The default is None, meaning generation continues until the maximum length is reached.---# Screenshot 2**Application:** Safari**Website URL:** codeacademy.com**Content:**- **Cheatsheets / Intro to OpenAI API**    **Intro to OpenAI GPT API**    **Related learning**    - **Free course**        Intro to OpenAI API        Explore OpenAI’s API and learn how to write more effective generative AI prompts that help improve your...        - **Beginner Friendly**    - **< 1 hour**    **OpenAI API**```Sure!   Starts In  : 0d 17h 54m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

I am interested in an agent that can help organize my work.

I don't mind for the agent to be creative about other forms of assistance!!

  Title      : Stanford AI Seminar
  When       : 2025-10-17 12:00:00-07:00 → 2025-10-17 13:00:00-07:00
  Location   : Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
  Starts In  : 0d 17h 46m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

user_description:
I am a CS PhD student (NLP) at Stanford.  
I work across several concurrent research projects.
I am interested in building personalized LLM tooling.
user_agent_goals:
I am interested in an agent that can help organize my work.
I would especially like an agent that keeps track of progress and if I have a meeting coming up for a particular project it can compile my results into slides or a report.
I also think an agent that finds related work and performs background literature review would be helpful.
Feedback on my writing is another welcome form of assistance.
I don't mind for the agent to be creative about other forms of assistance!!

Calendar Events (2 found):
  Title      : [AI Suggestion] Review IRB
  When       : 2025-10-17 10:45:00-07:00 → 2025-10-17 11:30:00-07:00
  Location   : <no location>
  Starts In  : 0d 16h 25m

----------

  Title      : Stanford AI Seminar
  When       : 2025-10-17 12:00:00-07:00 → 2025-10-17 13:00:00-07:00
  Location   : Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
  Starts In  : 0d 17h 40m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

  Title      : Stanford AI Seminar
  When       : 2025-10-17 12:00:00-07:00 → 2025-10-17 13:00:00-07:00
  Location   : Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
  Starts In  : 0d 17h 37m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

  Title      : Stanford AI Seminar
  When       : 2025-10-17 12:00:00-07:00 → 2025-10-17 13:00:00-07:00
  Location   : Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
  Starts In  : 0d 17h 30m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

user_description:
I am a CS PhD student (NLP) at Stanford.  
I work across several concurrent research projects.
I am interested in building personalized LLM tooling.
user_agent_goals:
I am interested in an agent that can help organize my work.
I would especially like an agent that keeps track of progress and if I have a meeting coming up for a particular project it can compile my results into slides or a report.
I also think an agent that finds related work and performs background literature review would be helpful.
Feedback on my writing is another welcome form of assistance.
I don't mind for the agent to be creative about other forms of assistance!!

Calendar Events (2 found):
  Title      : [AI Suggestion] Review IRB
  When       : 2025-10-17 10:45:00-07:00 → 2025-10-17 11:30:00-07:00
  Location   : <no location>
  Starts In  : 0d 16h 9m

----------

  Title      : Stanford AI Seminar
  When       : 2025-10-17 12:00:00-07:00 → 2025-10-17 13:00:00-07:00
  Location   : Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
  Starts In  : 0d 17h 24m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

  Starts In  : 0d 16h 54m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

  Title      : Stanford AI Seminar

  Starts In  : 0d 15h 56m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"

user_description:
I am a CS PhD student (NLP) at Stanford.  
I work across several concurrent research projects.
I am interested in building personalized LLM tooling.
user_agent_goals:
I am interested in an agent that can help organize my work.
I would especially like an agent that keeps track of progress and if I have a meeting coming up for a particular project it can compile my results into slides or a report.
I also think an agent that finds related work and performs background literature review would be helpful.
Feedback on my writing is another welcome form of assistance.
I don't mind for the agent to be creative about other forms of assistance!!

  Title      : Stanford AI Seminar
  When       : 2025-10-17 12:00:00-07:00 → 2025-10-17 13:00:00-07:00
  Location   : Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
  Starts In  : 0d 15h 43m
  Description:
    Hi everyone,
    
    With the goal of increasing collaboration across SAIL, we are starting the new Stanford AI Seminar. In this seminar series, held on the 3rd Friday of every month, a SAIL faculty member will present some of the latest results in their lab. We are hoping for a lively and interactive discussion that will foster a more connected SAIL community. (The seminar series will be in-person only.)
    
    Our first speaker, on 10/17, will be Percy Liang.
    
    The details for the first seminar are below. We are looking forward to seeing all of you there,
    Karen Liu and Carlos Guestrin (Seminar Organizers)
    
    Speaker: Percy Liang
    Date, Time Location: Friday 10/17 Noon in Gates 403 (Fujitsu)
                   Lunch will be served, please arrive early to get food
    
    Title: Marin: An Open Lab for Frontier AI
    
    Abstract:
    As AI capabilities skyrocket, openness plummets: the scientific community and broader public knows little of how frontier models (including open-weight models) are trained.  I will describe Marin, a radically new way of doing model development, inspired by true open-source software. Every experiment is done in the open, and anyone can suggest ideas, review, and even run experiments through GitHub, providing a better way of doing science that improves on preregistration, reproducibility, and peer review. I will discuss a selection of scientific results that have emerged from Marin, including the best open-source 32B model trained from scratch, rigorous benchmarking of optimizers and data-efficient training recipes. As we scale up, we hope that Marin can be a lab for the open research community to participate in the development of frontier AI.

----------"
